-### Stable GNOME OS blockers
-
-- Two different things
-    a) stable branches upgrade and switch (easier)
-    b) everything we need for an end user stable OS (hard)
-- Stable branches in sysupdate
-    - Andy Holmes working on it on systemd STF
-    - this is the only blocker for A
-- homed
-    - blocker for B, because migration
-    - we want this by default for everyone
-    - Abderrahim: homed with subvolumes short-term?
-        - Adrian: not a fan, we should wait for the file system stuff
-            - there's no way to migrate installations in the wild
-            - if we declare it stable we can not ask people to reinstall
-    - Jonas: can we do a reinstall on upgrade?
-        - back up your data, apps, etc. and reinstall?
-            - no, there's a lot more stuff
-    - Adrian: theoretically we could migrate, as long as we delete bytes as we copy them over, but otherwise we're running into disk size constraints
-        - needs to be done very carefully
-    - Abderrahim: what about migrating from subvolume?
-        - problem is there's no "send and destroy data at the source"
-        - even then, this breaks when the power goes out
-    - Adrian: homed has issues - resizing, multi-user, etc. don't work
-    - OS Pool
-        - the file system thing
-        - needed 
-        - btrfs on a sparse subvolume
-        - os pool is the sparse volume underneath
-        - Ada is working on this for STF
-        - was coordinated with the file system people
-        - need to change partitioning layout
-        - Ada: issue with one of the ideas we had
-            - need to look into scheduling/threading more
-        - 2 ideas for implementing it
-            - idea 1
-                - sparse volume sends an event that some space was used up by someone else
-                - there is a potential race associated with it
-            - idea 2
-                - file system asks to use some space, gets response
-- homed timeline
-    - if it takes 3 more years, we could message around this
-        - for community members it's fine to say it's "Beta" / "Preview" for now
-    - Adrian: "stable" means stable enough to give to OEMs
-    - everyone would be on board with making a public release, as long as we say it's preview/beta and we explain that you need to reinstall
-    - if we call it stable, we need to commit to it and support the configuration for a long time
-    - can we just have a migration script?
-        - hard, because we don't know how much free space there is, or how much we need
-    - Abderrahim: supporting indefinitely is something we could consider for the subvolumes - can we just keep both forever?
-        - Adrian: communication issue: we need to explain which one they're on, and why they're less secure
-            - every claim we we make needs to be "if you installed before X date then..."
-        - we could have a script/tool for experienced users, but there are a ton of edge cases
-            - we need to take the user account, delete it, move it to a homed user, etc.
-            - ask people to plug in an external drive to do it?
-- UI stuff
-    - New installer (includes new initial setup)?
-        - probably a blocker, the temporary one is janky
-        - Julian: simple version needs a few more months
-            - Adrian: there are still pending discussions upstream in systemd
-            - current version just uses repart directly
-                - we need to do sysinstall
-            - signed UKI?
-            - can't do this with the ESP
-            - background: Lennart implemented what we wanted already
-                - sticking point is kernel install, how is that supposed to work?
-                    - Lennart took kernel install and made a plugin that copies UKIs (??)
-                    - there's an active discussion about how the plugin was implemented
-                    - Adrian: there shouldn't be plugins in the first place
-                    - Abderrahim: how is this gonna work if the installer is itself the final system?
-                        - Adrian: works the same way, but repart will do the btrfs migration instead of copying the data
-                            - no, currently we take the UKI from the installer ESP, not from the rootfs
-                            - we don't know why you would do this with sysinstall
-            - needs discussion with Lennart tomorrow
-        - installer is blocked on the systemd sysinstall discussion...
-            - we can't copy the ESP, we need to copy individual files
-            - it's unsafe to ever overwrite an ESP - on some devices it bricks the firmware
-        - Lennart wants to land sysinstall this cycle
-        - Julian: please push Lennart to merge repart fixups
-        - Valentin: is the intial setup stuff done?
-            - no, only language is in there at the moment, nothing is done, everything is broken
-    - Updates in Settings?
-        - not a blocker
-        - we want it, but Software works for now
-- /etc merge
-    - Adrian: it's complicated in systemd, the issue is that we need to set up a confext early, potenitally in initrd, so that we have a writeable etc, the issue is that it installs in /var
-        - one of the maintainers has an installation when /var gets mounted on under boot for historical reasons,
-        - Adrian talked to Lennart and reached a consensus to break that historical behaviour, and Lennart will be okay with merging
-        - could convince Amutable to do it
-        - Valentin: hack the /etc/overlayfs?
-        - Adrian: confext takes /usr/share factory and /var and mounts them on top of each other
-        - Adrian: one easy way is to run confext in initrd
-        - Lennart proposed mounting /var in initrd
-        - Valentin to open a PR for running confext early in initrd
