-GNOME OS Sysupdate Install Instructions
-===
-
-
-The new images will encrypt your drive by default if it finds a TPM (even with secure boot disabled). They will also use a tpm2 device for verified boot and have `dm_verity`. However messing around with secure boot can potentially soft-brick your computer if you remove the wrong keys or the auto-setup-mode goes wrong. In such case you will have to reset the UEFI by shorting the CMOS jumper in the motherboard or taking the battery out. (Or reflashing the UEFI while offline if that's an option). 
-
-
-* Make sure to do this at your desktop first as it's generally easier to reset the UEFI settings/CMOS.
-* If you can only try this in a laptop, be aware it might potentially get soft-bricked if things go wrong enough. 
-* Double check if there's a way to reflash the firmware or reset it before hand.
-
-~~You can also avoid the secure-boot headache and install with secure-boot=disabled, however then you will have to encrypt your disk on your own. Easiest way though would be to setup systemd-homed in such case.~~ This is not true anymore. We always encrypt if we have a tpm2.
-
-## Download the installer from here:
-
-ISO: https://os.gnome.org/download/latest/gnome_os_installer.iso
-
-
-## Install:
-
-* Write the install into a usb stick
-    * If you want, you can also extract the disk.img and write that to a usb stick to avoid using a real harddrive for testingi
-* disable secure boot and run the install
-* Once install is done, go to the bios and enable secure-boot
-    * If it's a VM sd-boot will install the keys automatically See loader.conf(5) manual page, option `secure-boot-enroll`. 
-    * If there's a setup-mode set the bios to that, so sd-boot show an option int the boot menu to install the keys 
-      * One called "auto", which we recommend and has the Microsoft keys, one called "private" which does not have the Microsoft keys.
-      * :loudspeaker: ***Note from Valentin*** sometimes setup mode is just removing all keys)
-    * If there isn't a setup mode, you will have to append the PK.auth, KEK.auth and DB.auth files found in `loader/keys/auto/` to the respective EFI key variables.
-      Where you find the Secure Boot menu is in your BIOS, you usually have to go into "Custom/OtherOS" mode and then it should allow you to install your own keys.
-   
-* If you see a giant blue square saying stuff that's `Shim`, it's okay.
-    * If it complains about `security_violation` or so, something went wrong with the singatures. ask in the chat/post a picture.
-    
-* Hopefully by now you booted into initial setup with secure boot
-* Do normal initial setup.
-
-## Enable discard on the disks.
-
-There is no way currently to enable allow-disards on encrypted disks with systemd-gpt-auto-generator. There is also no way from systemd-repart to set it as default option on the volumes. So you will need to manually enable it.
-    
-```bash
-    sudo cryptsetup refresh root --allow-discards --persistent
-```
-
-## Build your own gnomeos update:
-
-  * :loudspeaker: ***Note from Valentin*** We need to add the notes from https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-build-meta/-/merge_requests/2418
-
-  * Build
-    ```bash
-    git clone https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-build-meta.git
-    cd gnome-build-meta
-    make KEY_ID="John Doe" IMPORT_MODE=local -C files/boot-keys
-    ./utils/run-sysupdate-repo.sh --devel
-    ```
-
-    Replace "John Doe" with the name you want.
-    
-    If you already created keys, maybe they are snake oil, you need to clean then before creating them again: `make clean -C files/boot-keys/`
-    
-    If you have several build directories, you should copy the keys, and at least `{VENDOR,SYSEXT}.{key,crt}`.
-
-  * Switch to another tty since we started a webserver in the above command
-
-  * Copy sysupdate files to `/etc`
-    ```bash
-    run0 cp -r /usr/lib/sysupdate*.d /etc/
-    ```
-  * Switch all the `Path=` in `/etc/sysupdate*/*.conf` files to `http://0.0.0.0:8080/``
-    ```bash
-    run0 sed -i 's,Path=https://.*,Path=http://0.0.0.0:8080/,' /etc/sysupdate*.d/*.conf
-    ```
-      * :loudspeaker: ***Note from Valentin*** Need to copy `/usr/lib/sysupdate*.d` first
-      * :loudspeaker: ***Note from Valentin*** If served from host when running in a VM, it is `10.0.2.2`. We should note that.
-  * Add verity certificates in `/etc` (only once):
-    Not having sysext signing keys in the kernel will confuse systemd-sysext and not mount any sysext. To avoid this, you can prepare your system to allow both upstream an local keys. You only need to do it once. Look for an extension already downloaded. For example here we have: `/var/lib/extensions/devel_nightly.677514.raw`.
-    ```bash
-    $ run0 mkdir -p /etc/verity.d
-    $ run0 cp files/boot-keys/SYSEXT.crt /etc/verity.d/mine.crt
-    $ run0 losetup -f -P --show /var/lib/extensions/devel_nightly.677514.raw
-    /dev/loop20
-    $ run0 cat /dev/loop20p3 | jq .signature -r | base64 -d | openssl pkcs7 -inform der -print_certs | run0 tee /etc/verity.d/upstream.crt
-    $ run0 losetup -d /dev/loop20
-    ```
-
-  * Enroll your Machine Owner Key (MOK) (only once)
-    ```bash
-    run0 mokutil --import files/boot-keys/VENDOR.der
-    ```
-    Set a password, remember it until next boot.
-    
-  * Wait for the build to finish
-
-  * Check the version. It is likely to be `l.1` on first build, but will increment.
-    ```
-    run0 /usr/lib/systemd/systemd-sysupdate
-    ```
-
-  * Update
-    ```bash
-    run0 /usr/lib/systemd/systemd-sysupdate update --verify=false l.1
-    run0 /usr/lib/systemd/systemd-sysupdate update --component=devel --verify=false l.1
-    ```
-      * :loudspeaker: ***Note from Valentin*** Instead of using `--verify=false`, we should add the key in `/etc/systemd/import-pubring.gpg`
-
-  * Reboot
-    On first reboot, you will be asked to enroll the Machine Owned Key (MOK). This is where you need to type the pasword.
-
-  * You will need to use recovery keys to unlock your disks. If you want to work with local builds for a longer time, you may re-enroll tpm2 keys. See section Re-enrolling the TPM2 if needed. But you will need to re-enroll again when switching back to upstream builds.
-
